Anonymous Sun 30 Jan 2022 08:10:19 No.45157962 Report
Quoted By: >>45158864 >>45160208
>>45157286
>it really is a wtf moment.
>every language has it to some degree and I suspect that in a world with anthros the dialects would be even wilder. The same word could have twenty different means depending on how you pronounced it
Thanks for bringing it back to /hmofa/, and storytelling in general. This is something that rarely gets the treatment it could &/or should. The incredible variability of language between regions and communities doesn't get exploited enough. In fact, almost never at all.

In an anthro world with multiple species, there would have to be so many sounds that can't be reproduced by every anthro universally. There wouldn't just one Common Tongue for an entire planet. It would be more like human Earth, with hundreds of languages. Even among humans we can't reliable hear or reproduce all sounds from different languages because we haven't been immersed in them from birth. It takes intense training and study to try and pick up quite a number of sounds, or combinations of sounds that don't usually occur together in your native language.

Now, multiply that factor by a dozen species with radically different hearing capability and methods of producing sounds.

We almost never get any treatment in a story about our human and anthro protagonists speaking different languages, let alone the insane difficulty in producing & recognizing sounds that are unique to the biological configuration of each. Beyond that, the mental configuration of each (biologically and psychologically) and their societal/cultural backgrounds would have very alien grammar structures for each.

One of the few stories that got extensive and well-done treatment on this topic was the Chanur series by C.J. Cherryh.

>40,000 in Gehenna
I wasn't expecting anyone to go that deep
What's struck me about her overarching world is that how things go wrong feels organic. Since 40,000iG, Morgaine, and Cyteen and all in the same universe, it takes a lot of dedication to work backward to a unified starting point (well before any of the books) and then think forward so you know why what's going wrong at the start of the first paragraph is going wrong.
It's a lesson that's even more applicable to fantasy, and that kind of worldbuilding is what I really consider the core of the term. Pretty bits of setting are garnishes compared to the things that drive your characters.
